snippet.textDisplay: Djokovic might have won his 17th grand slam title but it was not by any means an honorable victory. Thiem was game-wise the better player today but Djokovic ruined his rhythm by constantly acting weak, abusing medical time out, arguing with the umpire and purposely missing shots in the third set just to destabilize his opponent and mentally get in his head. As for Dominic Thiem, he is the future of tennis and he will learn to deal with this kind of cheating tactics. One day he will win multiple slams and be celebrated as a great champion. I'm with you, Domi, as is any other person who knows the meaning of the word "integrity".

snippet.textDisplay: Novak is fit, strong and tough but let’s face it, the last 7 years have been a cakewalk for him with Roger out of his prime, Nadal really being a one trick pony with clay (and his US Open victories were easy draws). So if anything, Novak is the one playing in a weak era. Not taking anything away from his achievements but we have to put things in perspective. We have seen what a peak player like Stan can handcuff Nole but unfortunately we haven’t seen that level from other players to challenge Novak. A peak Sampras, Federer or Stan would always give a peak Novak a lot of trouble, even a peak Nadal.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sorry Thiem but you don't have the mental power to beat Djokovic. And don't forget Djokovic didn't have the best day. Thiem has a lot of holes in his game: inconsistent first serve (he couldn't put pressure on Djokovic from the start), hit the balls too flat and as a result have a lot of unforced errors, when at net he doesn't know what to do with the ball, bad overheads and on top of these he is mentally weak.
Personally I don't like Djokovic's game as he just steals points instead of creating them. The only player that can beat Djokovic in grand slams is Wawrinka who has the power and consistency to destroy Djokovic on any surface. Unfortunately, Wawrinka really disappointed me in the game with Zverev.

snippet.textDisplay:
Djokovic is pretending unfocused and manipulating the whole game, i'm not saying bad about him.

He is definitely capable to take over his opponent, yet he choose not so fast to finish the game.


You can see the pattern of his playing through recent finals:
1. take the first set
2. "let" the opponent take at least one to two sets of the game
3. then, he gets back to his way
4. he'll try not to close the final set that radically
5. of the most, he does not take point by winning, but enormously by the errors of his opponent, which cannot be achieved if his skills is not much far ahead his opponent's, not a chance


I really think he is trying to make the game seems much more harder than it actually appears to him, which is also nice for the audience and the broadcasting rate, ye.
